To derive a two‐token string from S, we need

S → NT22 NT50  
NT22 ⇒* t142  
NT50 ⇒* t116  

But there is no rule NT22 → terminal (the only NT→terminal rules for t142 and t116 are NT52→t142 and NT68→t116), and NT22 only expands into two nonterminals, each of which must produce at least one terminal. Thus NT22 produces at least two terminals, NT50 at least one, so S produces ≥3 tokens. It cannot produce exactly two.  

No

To generate 3 terminals from S → NT22 NT50, we need either
- NT22 ⇒ 2 terminals and NT50 ⇒ 1 terminal, or
- NT22 ⇒ 1 terminal and NT50 ⇒ 2 terminals.

1) NT22 has no direct terminal rule, so its minimum yield is 2 tokens; NT50 does have NT50 → 't39' but no 't17', so it cannot yield the required 't17' as a single token.  
2) NT22 cannot yield exactly one token (no terminal rule), so the other split fails as well.

Hence S cannot derive a three‐token string t116 t76 t17.  
No

I applied the CYK algorithm.  The only nonterminals that produce the individual tokens are

  t56 → NT14  
  t145 → NT27  
  t169 → NT36  
  t116 → NT68  

When you look for any binary rule X → NT14 NT27 to cover the first two tokens, you find none; similarly there is no rule for NT27 NT36 or for NT36 NT68.  Hence no span of length 2 can be built, so you cannot build up to the full length 4.  Therefore the start symbol S cannot derive the string.

No

After populating the CYK table for the input “t179 t116 t116 t145 t66” (which gives NT-48, NT-68, NT-68, NT-27, NT-65 at length-1 spans) and attempting every split for S→NT22 NT50, no way is found to place NT22 over a left subspan and NT50 over the complementary right subspan. Thus the start symbol S cannot derive the given string.

No

After examining the start rule 

  S → NT22 NT50

we see that in any derivation the right‐hand child NT50 must eventually produce exactly one terminal (because its only terminal rule is NT50 → “t39”).  Thus any string generated by S must end in “t39.”  Our target string ends in “t116,” so it cannot be generated.

After checking all ways to split the five terminals between S → NT22 NT50, one finds that NT22 cannot yield the required prefix of t104 t114 … nor can NT50 cover the remaining suffix in any valid CNF parse. Therefore the string is not in the language.

After mapping terminals to their corresponding preterminals, the input string

  t145  t56  t39  t94  t56  t116

becomes the yield of

  NT27  NT14  NT50  NT61  NT14  NT68

and the start‐rule is

  S → NT22 NT50.

By inspection, NT50 can only derive either a single ‘t39’ or a subtree of size ≥2 so as to cover some suffix of length ≠{1,2,3,4} in this length‐6 string; and NT22 can only derive substrings whose lengths never line up so that the two children under S split the six terminals exactly into contiguous blocks.  No choice of splitting S → NT22 NT50 lets NT22 cover the prefix and NT50 cover the suffix of the six‐token string.  Therefore the grammar cannot generate

  t145 t56 t39 t94 t56 t116.
